  "fullDescription": "Maya (Sanskrit: ‡§Æ‡§æ‡§Ø‡§æ) is the cosmic illusion or power of delusion that veils the true nature of reality (Brahman) and creates the appearance of the phenomenal world. In Advaita Vedanta philosophy, maya is the mysterious power that makes the eternal, unchanging, singular Brahman appear as the diverse, changing material world. Maya is not simply 'illusion' in the sense of being unreal or false, but rather it is the mysterious creative power through which the formless takes form, the infinite appears as finite, and unity manifests as diversity. Under maya's influence, the individual soul (atman) forgets its true identity as Brahman and identifies with the limited body-mind complex, experiencing itself as separate from the divine. This misidentification leads to attachment, desire, suffering, and the cycle of rebirth. Liberation (moksha) comes through spiritual knowledge (jnana) that pierces the veil of maya and reveals the underlying unity of existence. Maya is sometimes personified as the creative shakti (power) of the divine.",
