      "symbolism": "Maya symbolizes the mysterious paradox of manifestation - how the infinite appears finite, how unity appears as multiplicity. It represents both the creative power that brings forth the cosmos and the deluding power that hides truth. Maya's veil symbolizes ignorance that can be lifted through knowledge. The comparison to a rope mistaken for a snake (classic Vedantic metaphor) illustrates maya's function - the rope (Brahman) is real, the snake (world) is apparent, and ignorance (maya) causes the misperception. Maya as divine feminine power (shakti) represents the generative, creative aspect of divinity.",
      "culturalSignificance": "Maya is fundamental to Hindu philosophical thought, particularly Advaita Vedanta. The concept influences approaches to spirituality, meditation, and the pursuit of knowledge. Understanding maya helps practitioners develop detachment from worldly phenomena while engaging with life skillfully. The concept has influenced Buddhism (as maya meaning illusion) and has entered global philosophical discourse. Modern physics' revelations about the insubstantial nature of matter and the role of observation in quantum mechanics have led to comparisons with maya. The concept is often misunderstood as mere denial of reality, when it actually affirms a deeper reality beyond appearances."
